"a.乏味的，枯燥的 【英】 adj. 乏味的，枯燥的(dull ; lifeless; vapid; flat; banal) 【考】 ruthless : mercy / insipid : flavor(无情不会仁慈/无味 不会有味道)insipid : invention / prosaic : imagination(枯燥的不会有创新/ 单调的不会有想象力) 【记】 in(进入)+sip(啜饮)+ id→不好喝的→乏味 的；注意：insipienc e(愚蠢) adj. (食物)无味的; 枯燥无味的 = dull = lifeless = vapid = flat = banal 【记】in进入, sip(v 吸吮; 啜饮), id－进入啜饮的状态, 说明东西不好喝的－无味的 【类】ruthless: mercy = insipid: flavor 无情不仁慈 = 无味没味道insipid: invention = prosaic: imagination枯燥的没有创新 = 单调的没有想象力 【反】piquant(adj 开胃的; 辛辣的) 【记】in 不 + sip 吸吮→不好吸的→乏味的 【相关】sip(吸吮)音：吸噗，吸啤(酒)，吸葡(萄洒)，吸品，吸一口茶品一品 insipid (adj.)  1610s, ""without taste or perceptible flavor,"" from French insipide (16c.), from Late Latin inspidus ""tasteless,"" from Latin in- ""not"" (see in- (1)) + sapidus ""tasty,"" from sapere ""have a taste"" (also ""be wise;"" see sapient). Figurative meaning ""uninteresting, dull"" first recorded 1640s, but it was also a secondary sense in Medieval Latin.In ye coach ... went Mrs. Barlow, the King's mistress and mother to ye Duke of Monmouth, a browne, beautifull, bold, but insipid creature. [John Evelyn, diary, Aug. 18, 1649] Related: Insipidly."
